9 Relating to Marshall County; to amend Section
10 45-48-111.03, Code of Alabama 1975; to require that the
11 presiding circuit judge, circuit clerk, and presiding district
12 judge are part of the committee to select the custodian of
13 voting tabulators; to clarify custodian responsibilities; and
14 to increase the custodian's salary.
15 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
16 Section 1. Section 45-48-111.03, Code of Alabama 1975,
17 is amended to read as follows:
18 "§45-48-111.03
19 (a) A custodian of voting machinestabulators shall be
20 appointed by a committee composed of the seniorpresiding
21 circuit judge, who shall also be the chair, the judge of
22 probate, tax collectorcircuit clerk, sheriff, and the county
23 judgepresiding district judge. SuchThe custodian of voting
24 machinestabulators shall have attended a recognized school
25 that teaches thetraining course that teaches operation and
26 handling of voting machinestabulators, or in lieu thereof must
27 have had at least three years' experience in the operation and
28 handling of voting machinestabulators.
Page 1

handling of voting machinestabulators.
HB193 INTRODUCED
29 (b) The custodian shall be responsible for performing
30 all duties as set out in Section 17-9-28necessary, or
31 incidental, to maintaining the county voting tabulators
32 including, but not limited to, the following:
33 (1) Testing all voting tabulators and comparing the
34 test results to the manufacturer's specifications ensuring a
35 perfect match.
36 (2) Installing new paper rolls in all tabulators.
37 (3) Clearing any testing totals.
38 (4) Sealing voting tabulator units for delivery to the
39 voting precincts.
40 (5) Testing all equipment for use by individuals under
41 the Americans with Disabilities Act (ADA) to ensure they are
42 working properly.
43 (6) Conducting a public test of the voting tabulators
44 as scheduled by the judge of probate.
45 (7) Resealing all public test units for delivery to the
46 voting precincts.
47 (8) Overseeing the delivery of equipment to the polling
48 precincts.
49 (9) Supporting the voting tabulators and ADA equipment
50 on election day.
51 (10) Overseeing the pickup of all voting tabulators and
52 ADA equipment and securing the tabulators and equipment at the
53 Marshall County Elections Warehouse.
54 (11) Charging voting equipment if required to ensure
55 that the machines are operational on election day.
56 (12) Testing all equipment for any recounts and
Page 2

(12) Testing all equipment for any recounts and
